# Browser Panel: WebContentsView Migration

## Summary

Migrated the browser panel from `<webview>` to `WebContentsView`. This resolved Google login, DevTools UX, Chrome extension support, and password manager detection. The multi-device responsive preview grid still uses `<webview>` (simpler, no auth needs).

## Why WebContentsView

`<webview>` is a guest/embedded browsing context. Sites detect this and block functionality:
- Google BotGuard blocks sign-in
- Extensions don't load properly (guest view behavior)
- Password managers (1Password, Bitwarden) can't detect form fields
- DevTools required a 150-line BrowserView host workaround

`WebContentsView` is a first-class browsing context — same as a regular browser tab. Eliminates the entire class of embedded-context problems.

## Architecture

### Main process
- `browser-view-manager.ts` — singleton managing all WebContentsViews
  - One view per browser tab (not per task — each tab has its own view)
  - LRU eviction: max 6 single-device views per task
  - `removeChildView`/`addChildView` for visibility (not `setVisible`, not offscreen bounds — neither worked)
  - `before-input-event` on each view intercepts Cmd/Ctrl shortcuts, forwards to renderer
  - `will-prevent-unload` bypass + 1s `forcefullyCrashRenderer` fallback for process cleanup
  - `reset()` called on `did-finish-load` and `render-process-gone` to clean orphaned views after reload

### Renderer hooks (composable, single-responsibility)
- `useBrowserViewLifecycle` — creates view on mount, destroys on unmount, retry on failure
- `useBrowserViewBounds` — rAF loop for position/size tracking + dialog overlay detection
- `useBrowserViewEvents` — subscribes to navigation/title/favicon events via IPC
- `useBrowserView` — thin composition of the above three

### Z-ordering (native views above DOM)
**What works:** One `document.querySelector` per frame in the rAF bounds loop:
```ts
const hasOverlay = !!document.querySelector(
  '[data-slot="dialog-overlay"], [data-slot="alert-dialog-overlay"], [data-slot="popover-content"]'
)
```
Calls `hideAll()`/`showAll()` which remove/add views from the window.

**What failed (3 attempts):**
1. React Context counter — duplicate module instances in monorepo bundler
2. Window global counter — counter leaks from startup dialogs
3. `useEffect` in `DialogContent` — React Compiler defers/optimizes effects unpredictably

**Key insight:** Never use React effects to control native Electron view visibility. The rAF loop is the single source of truth.

### Keyboard shortcuts
- `before-input-event` on each WebContentsView's webContents
- When `keyboardPassthrough = false` (default): all Cmd/Ctrl shortcuts intercepted
  - Main-process keys (Cmd+R, Cmd+,, etc.) → sent as same IPC the main handler would emit
  - Cmd+R from WebContentsView → reloads that view directly (`wc.reload()`)
  - All other Cmd/Ctrl → forwarded to renderer as synthetic `KeyboardEvent` on `window`
- When `keyboardPassthrough = true`: page gets all keys (toggled via toolbar button)
- Cmd+Shift+R → always reloads the app (renderer)

### Focus management
- `mainWindow.webContents.focus()` after `destroyView` and `hideAll` — prevents orphaned focus
- Click on placeholder div → `browser:focus` IPC → `wc.focus()`

### View lifecycle on reload
- `browserViewManager.reset()` on `did-finish-load` — cleans orphaned views after HMR/manual reload
- `browserViewManager.reset()` on `render-process-gone` — cleans before crash recovery

## Google Login — SOLVED

Google's BotGuard blocks Electron apps. Four changes required:

1. `app.commandLine.appendSwitch('disable-blink-features', 'AutomationControlled')` — `navigator.webdriver = false` natively
2. `contextBridge.executeInMainWorld` in `browser-chrome-preload.ts` — provides `chrome.app/csi/loadTimes` before page scripts (not via `Object.defineProperty` which BotGuard detects)
3. `app.userAgentFallback` — strips "Electron" and "slayzone" from UA
4. `onBeforeSendHeaders` — strips Electron from UA header (belt-and-suspenders)

**Key insight:** BotGuard needs REAL `chrome.runtime`, not stubs. `electron-chrome-extensions` provides this via session preload (same approach as Strawberry browser).

### What didn't work
- Spoofing `Sec-CH-UA` with "Google Chrome" — mismatch detected
- Firefox UA — BotGuard still detects Chromium
- CDP `Emulation.setUserAgentOverride` — debugger attachment is a bot signal
- `Object.defineProperty` patches — BotGuard checks `getOwnPropertyDescriptor`
- BrowserWindow instead of WebContentsView — same Chromium binary, same block

## Chrome Extensions — MV2 WORKS, MV3 BLOCKED

### Architecture
- `electron-chrome-extensions` (GPL) — Chrome extension API support
- `electron-chrome-web-store` (MIT) — extension directory, web store
- Extensions loaded via `session.loadExtension()` on `persist:browser-tabs`
- Tabs registered with `chromeExtensions.addTab(wc, win)` + `selectTab(wc)`

### What works (MV2)
- Content script injection, `chrome.runtime.sendMessage`, background pages
- Extension persistence (`browser-extensions.json`)
- Import from Chrome, Arc, Edge, Brave

### What doesn't work (MV3)
- `session.serviceWorkers.startWorkerForScope()` fails on partitioned sessions
- MV3 extensions (1Password, MetaMask) can't run background service workers
- Electron core limitation — not fixable in our code

## Passkeys / WebAuthn

Entitlements configured in `build/entitlements.mac.plist`:
- `com.apple.developer.web-browser` — web browsing capability
- `com.apple.developer.web-browser.public-key-credential` — passkey routing

Needs testing with signed build. 1Password macOS platform authenticator (not browser extension) should work.

## DevTools — SIMPLIFIED

Old: 150 lines of BrowserView host + CDP injection + device toolbar disabling + popup suppression.
New: `wc.openDevTools({ mode: 'bottom' | 'right' | 'undocked' | 'detach' })` — native docking inside the WebContentsView.

## Multi-device grid — KEPT ON WEBVIEW

`DeviceWebview.tsx` and `MultiDeviceGrid.tsx` still use `<webview>`. The responsive preview is for emulation, not auth/extensions. DOM-native layout is simpler for the drag-resize grid. `webviewTag: true` stays in `webPreferences`.

## Tests

63+ E2E tests across 8 files checking both bookkeeping AND native Electron state:
- `72-browser-view-lifecycle` — create, destroy, process death, tab switch visibility, LRU, partition
- `73-browser-view-bounds` — native bounds, setBounds, hideAll/showAll, rapid stress
- `74-browser-view-devtools` — all modes, toggle cycle, destroyed view edge cases
- `75-browser-view-navigation` — URL bar, IPC, back/forward, reload, tab isolation, invalid URL
- `76-browser-view-zorder` — real dialog hide/show, dropdown immunity, cross-task z-index
- `77-browser-view-focus` — focus IPC, click placeholder, queryable after focus
- `78-browser-view-scripting` — executeJs, DOM query/modify, insertCss/removeCss, zoom
- `79-browser-view-events` — did-navigate, canGoBack/Forward, title, dom-ready, did-fail-load
- `80-browser-view-google-login` — Google login E2E
- `81-browser-extension-usage` — MV2 extension content scripts + messaging

**Key testing insight:** Always check native Electron state (`getNativeChildViewCount`, `getActualNativeBounds`), not just manager bookkeeping (Map entries). The Map can be empty while orphaned native views still render.

